    Accomplished
    A free viewing gallery here was mandatory, as were others, but it's the attitude to that requirement which matters. As well as the spectacular views the visitor here sees the owners have seized the moment rather than begrudgingly accepted it. Go. It's glorious. Minimalist, expansive, breathtaking. The coffee is expensive but good (and they'll let you sit by a window while drinking it). Best of all you can see all your old favourites (and won't have to see the one you're on because it ain't a looker). It's not only higher than The View from you-know-what, it's better as an experience than it.

    Free panoramic London views
    Wow! Stunning views. Plenty of space to roam around. Floor to ceiling windows give extensive panoramic views. Simon, team leader very knowledgeable. All staff friendly and welcoming. There's no rushing you through so that more people can enter. There are some seats near kiosk where you can purchase refreshments. A few more further round would be welcome. Be aware you enter on one side of building and exit the other. We were lucky enough to get a walk in ticket. If you're in the area it's worth asking if there are any tickets available, unlikely at weekends.

    Awesome views of London
    Visited in October 2023 during a weekday. Accessing the event was straight-forward and staff (reception, security and lift wardens) were friendly and helpful. There were definitely no crowds relative to those, for example, at the sky garden in the walkie talkie building or the Shard. Views of London are impressive and, in my opinion, more so than those experienced from the Shard. As this is an in-door experience, the only downside is the level of glare from the window and associated shadows which is something to bear in mind when taking photos here. Worth booking tickets in advance as these sell out very quickly. Overall, the views were memorable and definitely worth the visit.

Excellent views of London - and free
Oct 2024 Couples
Ive been to plenty of rooftop bars etc and to the sky garden. Horizon 22 is the place to go if you are looking for good views and a chance to see London from the highest viewing platform.
Its completely free and you can take all the time you want to enjoy the view and take photos.
For anyone bemoaning a lack of seats or facilities- if youre looking for somewhere to sit for a long chat etc this isnt the place for that. There are very few places left in central London which are genuinely free, with no expectation of consumer spending or donation etc.
This is a pleasant change from the typical consumerism.
There are toilets and a small cafe at the platform level. You need to go through security to enter.

David D
Devon, UK27,505 contributions
In a word - AMAZING - We loved everything about our visit
Oct 2024 Couples
Wednesday 2nd October we booked an an appointment to visit this viewing platform with views stretching across London.

Our booked slot was between 14.00 and 14.30, we turned up a bit early, were scanned in and ushered through. Having passed through the scanner and security we were escorted to the next available elevator (lift).

The elevator whisked us up to the 58th floor, from there we walked down to the viewing platform which offers 300 degree views of London's skyline.

Part of the enjoyment of walking around the platform was picking out the sights we recognised and seeing them from a different perspective, a bird's eye view.

From here we could follow the flow of the River Thames identifying it's bridges and famous landmarks along the way. These included Tower of London, Tower Bridge, City Hall, The Shard, London, Houses of Parliament, Big Ben and so very much more. The views stretched as far as the eye could see.

One of our favourite bits was looking down on the Gherkin. It was like a bit of revenge as we walked by the building earlier and looking up it we felt small and insignificant, now we were looking down on it.

We did have a coffee and a sandwich at the cafe on the platform. Both were good, reasonably priced, definitely not a rip off place, cheaper than some of the cafes outside on ground level.

Everything about here was impressive, the viewing platform and the stunning views, everywhere was spotlessly clean and still looking new.

The staff here were absolutely delightful and charming, they were so appreciative that we had visited this landmark where they worked and it was apparent that they all loved what job they did and were so happy to help.

The most amazing bit was the this wonderful experience was free, there was no admission fee.

The weather at the time of our visit was a bit dark and overcast but that did not spoil our enjoyment or the views.
Written October 15, 2024

Nothing is FREE in 2024, except the Horizon 22
Sep 2024 Couples
A day in London and searching for things to do. The queue for the Shard was shocking and they were going to charge 57 so we kept on walking and came across the Horizon 22. We checked for tickets expecting it to be fully booked however they were available immediately, so we booked and off up we went. How this is possibly free is beyond me, nothing in 2024 is free especially in London! The views are excellent, Tower Bridge, Tower of London, The Shard, London Eye and towards Buckingham Palace. The lift is quick, there is a cafe that we got some drinks and cookies and enjoyed a small picnic sitting on the floor by the window, with a spectacular view. Hands down I will be recommending this to anyone going to London.
